e: Temptations and Challenges in Canada’s Aid Program, the editors bring together diverse perspectives to investigate whether aid for good governance works. The first section of the book outlines the changing face of international development assistance and ideas of good governance. The second section analyzes six nations: three are countries to which Canada has devoted a significant portion of its aid efforts over the past five to ten years: Ghana, Vietnam, and Bangladesh. Two are newer and more complex “fragile states,” where Canada has engaged: Haiti and Afghanistan. These five are then compared with Mauritius, which has enjoyed relatively good governance. The final section looks at challenges and new directions for Canadas development policy. Co-published with the Centre for International Governance Innovation  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAide économique canadiennexAspect politiquexPays en voie de développement. 0aAide économique canadiennexPays en voie de développement. 0aAide économiquexCas, Études dexPays en voie de développement. 0aConditionality (International relations)xDeveloping countries. 0aConditionality (International relations)zDeveloping countries. 0aConditionnalité (Relations internationales)xPays en voie de développement. 0aEconomic assistancexCase studiesxDeveloping countries. 0aEconomic assistancezDeveloping countriesvCase studies. 0aEconomic assistance, CanadianxDeveloping countries. 0aEconomic assistance, CanadianxPolitical aspectsxDeveloping countries. 0aEconomic assistance, CanadianxPolitical aspectszDeveloping countries. 0aEconomic assistance, CanadianzDeveloping countries. 0aInternational organization. 0aOrganisation internationalexKanadaxEntwicklungsländerxDeveloping countries. 4aPolitical Science. 4aPolitical Science: International Relati